[6] Human to human transmission
Date: 9 May 2017
Source: Chinese Medical Journal [summarized, edited]
http://www.cmj.org/article.asp?issn=0366-6999;year=2017;volume=130;issue=10;spage=1255;epage=1256;aulast=Zhang


Abstract:
Since throat swab specimens obtained from 3 adult Chinese patients were confirmed as an avian-origin influenza A(H7N9) virus by local Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 2013,[1] many confirmed cases have been reported in Mainland of China. Although family and hospital clusters with confirmed or suspected avian H7N9 virus infection were previously reported, and person-to-person transmission was put forward, human infection of H7N9 appears to be associated with exposure to infected live poultry or contaminated environments [2], and no clear evidence has proved that it could transmit from person to person. Here, we report a case confirmed with H7N9 after intimate contact with his H7N9 ward mate; it may be the 1st case infected between ward mates in a ward, so we report it here.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The report by Zhang et al is based on transmission of infection from a confirmed case of influenza A/H7N9 infection to another patient as a result of cohabitation in the same room for nearly 20 hours.

Other studies have shown that nearly 68 percent of infected cases have a history of visiting the live poultry market or exposure to market poultry, even without direct (touching) or indirect (within one meter) contact. [Liu B, Havers F, Chen E, Yuan Z, Yuan H, Ou J, et al. Risk factors for influenza A (H7N9) disease - China, 2013. Clin Infect Dis 2014;59:787-94. doi: 10.1093/cid/ciu423>].

Even though human-to-human transmission has rarely been confirmed, there have been some case reports of clusters in many cities of China. In this report, the authors state that "the 2nd case in this report had physical contact with the index case when assisting the index case to the bathroom (it lasted for 10 min) and had no history of exposure to live poultry or LPMs before the illness onset." How long (duration) and what direct physical contact would constitute serious risk? - Mod.UBA]

******
[7] Biological characterisation of A(H7N9) viruses in humans
Date: 11 May 2017
Source: Eurosurveillance [edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=22798


With no or low virulence in poultry, avian influenza A(H7N9) virus has caused severe infections in humans. In the current 5th epidemic wave, a highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) H7N9 virus emerged. The insertion of 4 amino acids (KRTA) at the haemagglutinin (HA) cleavage site enabled trypsin-independent infectivity of this virus. Although maintaining dual receptor-binding preference, its HA antigenicity was distinct from low-pathogenic avian influenza A(H7N9). The neuraminidase substitution R292K conferred a multidrug resistance phenotype.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The article by Zhu et al describes some key features of influenza A/H7N9 viruses, including:

- low pathogenicity avian influenza (LPAI) A/H7N9 poses a higher risk for humans than highly pathogenic (HPAI) H5N1 because LPAI H7N9 can bind sialic acid alpha-2,6 human-type receptors, while HPAI H5N1 could not.
- The study data show the HPAI H7N9 viruses retain dual receptor binding properties, with slightly increased binding preference for both [human and avian] receptors compared with LPAI H7N9 viruses.
- It is well known that human upper respiratory tissues and trachea contain mainly alpha-2,6 receptors while lung tissue possesses mixtures of avian type alpha-2,3 and human type alpha-2,6 receptors [DOI: 10.1038/nbt1375 PMID: 18176555].
- The persisting preference for both avian- and human-type receptors of HPAI H7N9 viruses may result in their circulation in poultry and possible transmission among humans.

It has already been observed that the number of human cases of influenza A/H7N9 has increased in the current wave with more opportunities for the virus to evolve and potentially develop better transmission fitness. - Mod.UBA

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5030458,155.]
